3 Closeness - centrality based on distance to others in the graph

How close an actor to all the other actors in network?

High closeness centrality - short communication path to others, minimal number of steps to reach others.

Answers the “Kevin Bacon” question:

How many steps are required to access every other vertex from a given vertex?

One practical implication of this metric: it helps you gauge how information might spread within your network, and who might be the best people to leverage if you need to make sure information gets around. Link here: http://www.tc.umn.edu/~alink/R-social-network-analysis.html

Closeness centrality can be defined as a measure of how far other nodes are from the node in question. Nodes with high closeness centrality are likely to be relatively efficient in receiving or transmitting information to/from distant parts of the social network.

Scores may be interpreted as arising from a reciprocal process in which the centrality of each actor is proportional to the sum of the centralities of those actors to whom he or she is connected.

In general, vertices with high eigenvector centralities are those which are connected to many other vertices which are, in turn, connected to many others (and so on). (The perceptive may realize that this implies that the largest values will be obtained by individuals in large cliques (or high-density substructures)

3.1.1 Saving to Igraph object

V(var6)$incloseness <- closeness(var6, mode = "in", weights = E(var6)$var6) %>% round(6)
V(var6)$outcloseness <- closeness(var6, mode = "out", weights = E(var6)$var6) %>% round(6)
V(var6)$totalcloseness <- closeness(var6, mode = "total", weights = E(var6)$var6) %>% round(4)

3.1.2 Saving to Environment

var6_incloseness<- closeness(var6, mode = "in", weights = E(var6)$var6) %>% round(6)
var6_outcloseness<- closeness(var6, mode = "out", weights = E(var6)$var6) %>% round(6)
var6_totalcloseness<- closeness(var6, mode = "total", weights = E(var6)$var6) %>% round(6)

3.2.1 Network Plotting Based On Non-normalized Closeness - IN

V(var6)$incloseness<-closeness(var6, weights = E(var6)$var6, mode="in")

#Get Variable
V(var6)$var6_color_degree<-round(V(var6)$incloseness,6)

#Creating brewer pallette
vertex_var6_color_degree<-
  colorRampPalette(brewer.pal(length(unique(
          V(var6)$var6_color_degree)), "RdBu"))(
            length(unique(V(var6)$var6_color_degree)))

#Saving as Vertex properties 
V(var6)$vertex_var6_color_degree<-
  vertex_var6_color_degree[as.numeric(
  cut(V(var6)$var6_color_degree,
      breaks=length(unique(V(var6)$var6_color_degree))))]

set.seed(123)
#Plotting based only on degree measures 
edge.start <- ends(var6, es=E(var6), names=F)[,1]

# Fixing ego
minC <- rep(-Inf, vcount(var6))
maxC <- rep(Inf, vcount(var6))
minC[1] <- maxC[1] <- 0
co <- layout_with_fr(var6, niter=10^4, minx=minC, maxx=maxC,miny=minC, maxy=maxC, weights = E(var6)$weight)


#PLotting
plot(var6, 
     layout=co,
     edge.color=V(var6)$vertex_var6_color_degree[edge.start],
     edge.arrow.size=closeness(var6, weights = E(var6)$var6, mode="in"),
     edge.width=E(var6)$weight/mean(E(var6)$weight),
     edge.curved = TRUE,
     vertex.color=V(var6)$vertex_var6_color_degree,
     vertex.size=closeness(var6, weights = E(var6)$var6, mode="in")*10^5,
     vertex.frame.color="black",
     vertex.label.color="black",
     vertex.label=get.vertex.attribute(var6,"LABEL_COR"),
     vertex.label.cex=(closeness(var6, weights = E(var6)$var6, mode="in")+10^-5)*2000,
     vertex.label.dist=0,
     rescale=F,
     xlim=range(co[,1]), 
     ylim=range(co[,2])
     )
axis(1)
axis(2)


#Solving Problems with legend rendering 
a<-V(var6)$var6_color_degree
b<-V(var6)$vertex_var6_color_degree
c<-table(a,b)
d<-as.data.frame(c)
e<-subset(d, d$Freq>0)
e<-e[order(e$a,decreasing=T),] 
f<-t(e$a)
g<-t(e$b)

#Adding Legend
legend(x=range(co[,1])[2], 
       y=range(co[,2])[2],
       legend=as.character(f),
       pch=21,
       col = "#777777", 
       pt.bg=as.character(g),
       pt.cex=2,
       bty="n", 
       ncol=1,
       lty=1,
       cex = .3)

#Adding Title
  title("Network Closeness Degree Sized and Colored In - 8_RECEBER TREINAMENTOS CAPACITAÇÕES (var6)", sub = "Source: from authors ")
  text( 
    x=range(co[,1])[1],
    y=range(co[,2])[1], 
      labels = sprintf(
             "Median In Closennes:%.4f\nSD In Closennes: %.5f",
             median(closeness(var6, mode="in", weights = E(var6)$var6)), 
             sd(closeness(var6, mode="in", weights = E(var6)$var6))
             )
       )

var6_df_closseness<-var6_df_closseness[c("Type","In Closeness", "Out Closeness", "Total Closeness","In Closeness Normalized", "Out Closeness Normalized","Total Closeness Normalized", "Centralization Closeness")]

4.4 Aggregating data from previous table - mean

aggdata_mean <-aggregate(var6_df_closseness, by=list(var6_df_closseness$Type), FUN=mean, na.rm=TRUE)

names(aggdata_mean) <- c("Group","Type","In Closeness(M)", "Out Closeness(M)", "Total Closeness(M)","In Closeness Normalized(M)", "Out Closeness Normalized(M)", "Total Closeness Normalized(M)","Centralization Closeness(M)")
  
#Removing Type variable
aggdata_mean<-aggdata_mean[,-c(2)]

4.5 Aggregating data from previous table - sd

aggdata_sd <-aggregate(var6_df_closseness, by=list(var6_df_closseness$Type), FUN=sd, na.rm=TRUE) 

names(aggdata_sd) <- c("Group","Type","In Closeness(SD)", "Out Closeness(SD)", "Total Closeness(SD)","In Closeness Normalized(SD)", "Out Closeness Normalized(SD)", "Total Closeness Normalized(SD)", "Centralization Closeness(SD)")

#Removing Type variable
aggdata_sd<-aggdata_sd[,-c(2)]

#Merging mean and standart deviation
total_table <- merge(aggdata_mean,aggdata_sd,by="Group")

#Rounding
Group<-total_table[,c(1)] #Keeping group
total_table<-total_table[,-c(1)] %>% round(6) #Rouding
total_table<-cbind(Group,total_table) #Binding toghter

#Organizing Variabels
total_table<-total_table[c("Group","In Closeness(M)", "In Closeness(SD)", "Out Closeness(M)", "Out Closeness(SD)", "Total Closeness(M)","Total Closeness(SD)","In Closeness Normalized(M)", "In Closeness Normalized(SD)", "Out Closeness Normalized(M)", "Out Closeness Normalized(SD)", "Total Closeness Normalized(M)","Total Closeness Normalized(SD)", "Centralization Closeness(M)","Centralization Closeness(SD)")]
